Anostraca (Pancrustacea: Branchiopoda ) is a globally distributed and relatively small order that includes about 353 species belonging to 42 genera and 8 families (
Brendonck et al. 2008
; Rogers 2013). This taxon, usually known as fairy shrimps, is a morphologically conserved group, well characterized by an elongated body shape, mobile appendices (thoracopods) and a bifurcated telson (with a paired cercopods) (Rogers et al. 2020). Also, fairy shrimps exhibit remarkable sexual dimorphism. Male antennae are highly modified as a frontal appendage with copulatory function, while in females the antennae are immobile and simple ( Alonso 1996 ). This group also presents a characteristic behavior including upside-down swimming in the water column where they filter-feed. They usually inhabit freshwater environments, such as temporary ponds, lagoons, rain pools and puddles, high mountain lakes, rock pools and also continental hyper-saline environments (
Brendonck et al. 2008
;
Rodríguez-Flores et al. 2016
). In these habitats, fairy shrimps confront the unfavorable and unpredictable climate conditions by developing a short life cycle and drought resistant resting eggs (cysts), which remain in diapause until favorable conditions exist. This egg phase plays a key role to the species passive dispersal, even allowing oceanic islands colonization ( Graham & Wirth 2008 ;
Waterkeyn et al. 2010
). Shape and ornamentation of the egg surface can facilitate dispersion by holding on to the dispersal agents (i.e. animal skin), and are usually used as useful diagnostic characters for taxonomic studies (
Brendonck et al. 1992
, 2008 ; Mura 1992 ; Rogers 2014d ).

The Afrotropical region is one of the richest areas of Anostraca , where five families and more than 56 species have been recorded (
Brendonck et al. 2008
;
Nhiwatiwa et al. 2017
). However, many areas of sub-Saharan Africa still remain largely unexplored (
Brendonck et al. 2008
, 2015 ;
Nhiwatiwa et al. 2017
; Rogers & Meyer-Milne 2021 ). In Senegal , three species of Anostraca have been recorded: Streptocephalus zeltneri Daday, 1910
, S . sudanicus Daday, 1910
(Family Streptocephalidae Daday, 1910 ), and Branchinella ( Branchinellites ) chudeaui (Daday, 1910)
(Family
Thamnocephalidae Packard, 1883 ). In addition, an unidentified species of Artemia has been found in several localities in Senegal (
Vanhaecke et al. 1987
;
Kaiser et al. 2006
; Muñoz & Pacios 2010 ). Branchinella ( Branchinellites ) chudeaui is known from two eco-regions of Senegal : in the Sahel at Ndilla (close to Linguère) ( Monod 1969 ) and in the West Sudanian savanna at Poull Koz and Poull Bourgou (near Tambacounda ) ( Gauthier 1951 ). The type locality of B . ( B .) chudeaui , “Bassin du Moyen-Niger, Simbidissi”, is currently dubious as it could be either in Mali and Niger . Additionally, B. ( B. ) chudeaui is present in Chad , Niger and Gambia ( Belk & Brtek 1995 ). Streptocephalus zeltneri was described from Yélimane and S . sudanicus from Nioro, previously within the French Sudan territory, which nowadays belongs to Mali ( Daday 1910b ). In Senegal , Streptocephalus sudanicus and S. zeltneri were also recorded in two localities around Ndilla, in the Sahel ( Monod 1969 ; Hamer 1994;
Hamer et al. 1994b
). In addition, Gauthier (1951) recorded an unidentified population of Streptocephalus in Poull Bourgou, in the Sudanian savanna of Senegal . Streptocephalus sudanicus also occurs in Mali , Niger and Sudan (
Brendonck et al. 1992
), while the range of S. zeltneri is limited to Senegal and its type locality in Mali (
Hamer et al. 1994b
).

StreptocephalusBaird, 1852 is the only genus of the family Streptocephalidae Daday, 1910 , and its origins date back to the Jurassic (
Daniels et al. 2004
). It is the largest genus of Anostraca and currently encompasses 65 species (Rogers 2013; Rogers & Padhye 2014 ) distributed in North America, Australia , Africa and Eurasia. Currently, 36 species of Streptocephalus are known from Africa, including Madagascar ( Brendonck & Belk 1993 ; Hamer 1994;
Beladjal et al. 1996
;
Rogers et al. 2013
). However, considering the poor knowledge of the distribution and diversity patterns of Anostraca in Africa, and that just a few phylogeographic studies have been conducted ( Halliburton & Graham 2017 ;
Kappas et al. 2017
), the true diversity is likely underestimated, especially in putatively widely distributed species (
Daniels et al. 2004
).

Study area and sampling. The study area is mainly located in Senegal , a west African country ( 196.712 km2 ) bordered by Mauritania to the north, Mali in the east, Guinea in the southeast and Guinea-Bissau in the southwest. It is also bordered by the Atlantic Ocean in the west. A smaller country, Gambia , is embedded within Senegal , extending from the Atlantic coast throughout the Gambia River to the center of Senegal . Senegal typically presents a tropical savanna climate in the south, an arid, hot steppe climate in the central region and an arid, hot desert climate in the north (
Peel et al . 2007
). The dry season ranges from December to April and is dominated by the hot, dry, harmattan wind (
Youm et al. 2005
). Rainfall increases southwards, with extreme annual precipitation range from 250 mm in the north to 1800 mm in the south. Despite the low ( 0–648 m asl) and flat land topography (no remarkable mountainous system is known within the territory), its geographic location is affected by a transitional climatic zone, resulting in a high habitat diversity (
Fall et al. 2006
). The main classified eco-regions are latitudinally distributed, from north to the south: Sahelian Acacia savanna, West Sudaninan savanna, and Guinean forest-savanna mosaic (
) (WWF 2000).

Several temporary freshwater ponds of different properties were sampled in August 2015 , coinciding with the rainy season. Sampling localities extended across the three main eco-regions (
). Specimens were collected from eleven ponds, four of those were located within the Sahelian eco-region, six within the western Sudanese savanna (although three of those were close to the limits of the Guinean forest-savanna mosaic) and one within the Guinean forest-savanna mosaic (
). A total of 315 specimens of Anostraca were collected and preserved in absolute ethanol. Thirty-eight specimens were used for molecular analyses ( Table 1 ) and 277 were morphologically examined and housed in the Museo Nacional de Ciencias Naturales (MNCN-CSIC), Madrid , Spain ( Table 2 ).

Mitochondrial Cytochrome c Oxidase I gene ( cox1 ) and Nuclear Internal Transcribed Spacer 2 ( ITS2 ) markers were analyzed in this work. Polymerase chain reaction (PCR) was used to amplify the barcoding fragment of the cox1 employing the primers LCO1490 /HCO2198 (
Folmer et al. 1994
) and the ITS2 fragment by using the primers CAS5p8sFt/CAS28sB1d. Both cox1 and ITS2 PCR reactions were performed in 25 μl reaction volume that contained 2μl of extracted DNA, 1 μl dNTP, 2.5 μl of reaction buffer 10 (Tris-HCl, pH=8.3, Biotools), 0.8 μl of MgCl2 (50Mm), 0.5 μl of each primer (10Mm), 17.3 μl of distilled water and 0.4 μl Taq DNA polymerase (Biotools, 5 ud/µl). PCR reactions consisted of 40 cycles at a denaturing temperature of 94°C (60s), annealing at 48°C (60s), and extension at 72°C (60s). PCR products were visualized by electrophoresis in a 1.5% agarose gel. Samples that contained visible and single bands were sequenced at Macrogen Inc. (Macrogen Europe, Madrid , Spain ).

All sequences were edited using Sequencher (1991–2002 Gene Codes Corporation), and then, aligned in MAFFT (
Katoh & Toh 2008
). This dataset was also checked in Mesquite v 3.40 (
Maddison & Maddison 2018
) to revise the alignments.

Morphology.
Dissections were made under a Wild M3 stereomicroscope, and drawings with the help of a camera lucida attached to an Olympus BH-2 compound microscope equipped with phase contrast optics. Examination and photographs of ethanol-preserved specimens were performed using a Leica MZ16A stereo microscope. The morphology of the eggs was examined by Environmental Scanning Electron microscopic (SEM) with a FEI Inspect S50 SEM and low vacuum conditions, using either BSED and LFD detectors for different structures (
Recuero & Rodríguez-Flores 2020
) (

). Dissected and drawn specimens were not preserved.

Phylogenetic analysis and genetic divergences. Phylogenetic analyses were carried out based on the coxI and ITS2 concatenated matrix under Bayesian Inference in MrBayes 3.2.6 (
Ronquist et al. 2012
) (
). The data matrix was composed of five specimens of Streptocephalus sudanicus , 12 of S. zeltneri ,
21 of a new undescribed taxon, one of S. torvicornisWaga, 1842 , and two of S. mackiniMoore, 1966 . Chirocephalus diaphanus Prévost, 1820
, Branchinecta orientalisSars, 1901 , and B . ferox ( Milne-Edwards, 1840 )
were used as outgroups (codes: LT821335 , LT821352 , LT821337 , LT821353 , LT821327 , LT821344 , LT821331 , LT821348 ;
Rodríguez-Flores et al . 2017
). Selection of the best substitution model for each marker was carried out setting the command prset aamodelpr to mixed . Four Markov Chains Monte Carlo (MCMC) were run for 5x 106 generations sampling every 1000 generations. A majority consensus tree was reconstructed after discarding the first 20000 sampled trees as burn-in. Streptocephalus mackini from Mexico and S. torvicornis from Morocco were used to provide a phylogenetic background for the Senegalese specimens. Uncorrected p-distances for each gene of the five species of Streptocephalus included in the analysis were calculated in PAUP v. 4.0a167 ( Swofford 2002 ) ( Table 3 ).

Four freshwater species of Anostraca were found in Senegal . Streptocephalus zeltneri was recorded in three localities within the Sudanian savanna ecoregion (
); S. sudanicus was found in two localities at the Sudanian savanna ecoregion and B. ( B .) chudeaui was found in two localities within the Sahel (
). An undescribed taxon, whose adults were visually similar to those of S. zeltneri was found in five localities across the three Senegalese ecoregions (
,
). Detailed morphological and molecular analyses were congruent and support the hypothesis of a new evolutionary lineage occurring in Senegal . In the pond located in Tambacounda , Diabal, S . sudanicus and the new taxon were found in syntopy.

