sec.p:
We have updated the distribution of the freshwater anostracan species in Senegal ( Gauthier 1951 ; Monod 1969 ; Hamer 1994;
Hamer et al . 1994b
). With the newly discovered species, S. wolof sp. nov. ,
the diversity of freshwater Anostraca of Senegal is raised to four species. Two of them, S. wolof and S. zeltneri are sister cryptic species. The designation of these two lineages with a particular name relied on the morphological characters of the eggs. The unkeeled ribs of the eggs of S . zeltneri , as described and figured in Brendonck & Coomans (1994) , differ from those in S . wolof , in which the ribs are keeled (
). In certain anostracan lineages, egg morphology is not taxonomically informative due to their great variability (within and between populations) in terms of size and different development of the ribs that ornament the egg surface ( Belk & Rogers 2002 ;
Zarattini et al. 2013
), and also because of the great homoplasy that this character displays (
Daniels et al. 2004
; Rogers & Aguilar 2020 ). However, the morphology of the revised eggs among different populations of S. wolof and S. zeltneri , are fully congruent with the phylogenetic lineage, suggesting that in this case can be used as a diagnostic trait independently fixed during the evolutionary history of each species. Due to the morphological uniformity between adults of S. wolof and S. zeltneri , previous records of S. zeltneri from central Senegal remain in need of revision.

The causes of speciation are not evident. No traces of hybridization have been found between S. zeltneri and S. wolof , despite they occur in similar environments, geographically close between each other (separated by no more than 175 km ). The genetically homogeneous pattern depicted by the examined populations of S . wolof , even those separated by 530 km , could be derived from the existence of relatively recent gene flow events. As passive dispersion at local scale of Anostraca driven by large vertebrates seems not a rare event in Africa (
Vanschoenwinkel et al. 2011
), sympatry of S. wolof and S. zeltneri could be expected, suggesting currently complete reproductive isolation between them. Recent connectivity among intraspecific populations of S . zeltneri and S . wolof is expected based on the low genetic distance within each species ( Table 3 ), which present similar ecological requirements. In this sense, speciation driven by ecological niche segregation is not supported ( Rogers 2014d ). Allopatric speciation due to founder effect, followed by subsequent regional monopolization, seem to be feasible ( Wiman 1979 ;
De Meester et al. 2002
; Rogers 2014a –d). According to the genetic divergences among S . zeltneri and the new species, and considering the general rate of nucleotide substitution employed in time-calibrated phylogenies of related taxa (
Reniers et al. 2013
;
Lindholm et al. 2016
;
Rodríguez-Flores et al. 2017
, 2020), these values might imply Upper Miocene-Pliocene divergences.

In addition to the absence of gene flow between Streptocephalus zeltneri and S. wolof , they show a marked mitochondrial ( coxI ) genetic divergence, similar to those depicted by some well-recognized species of Streptocephalus (
Daniels et al . 2004
)
. Regarding the nuclear ( ITS1 ), genetic distances between S. wolof and S. zeltneri are also congruent to those between morphologically distinct or cryptic species of Anostraca (
Daniels et al . 2004
;
Lukić et al. 2019
).

The Afrotropical region, in spite of being a diversity hotspot for large Branchiopoda (
Brendonck et al . 2008
; Rogers 2013;
Brendonck et al . 2015
), is the one of the most unexplored and under-sampled areas. The majority of studies of large Branchiopoda from Africa have been carried out in southern Africa ( South Africa , Namibia and Zimbabwe ), while the fauna of Anostraca from the rest of the continent is still poorly known ( Hamer & Brendonck 1997 ;
Brendonck et al . 2008
;
Nhiwatiwa et al . 2014
;
Nhiwatiwa et al . 2017
). Indeed, Streptocephalus has not been recorded in Central Africa yet. It has been reported that the great species diversity displayed in Streptocephalus was due to its African origin and posterior vicariant events during Gondwana fragmentation (
Daniels et al . 2004
). These geological processes may have led to the spread and diversification of Streptocephalus to other warm areas across Nearctic, Palearctic, African and Indo-Malayan regions (
Sanoamuang et al. 2000
, 2002 ;
Maeda-Martínez et al. 2005
;
Nhiwatiwa et al. 2017
;
Kappas et al. 2017
), but kept them out of Southern America, Antarctic, New Zealand and a wide area of Australia . These data lead to the assumption that the absence of records is likely caused by lack of exploration rather than being a real distribution pattern and that further new records of either described species and new taxa are yet to be discovered through Central Africa. Our results highlight the importance of exploration of under sampled areas and study phylogeographic patterns of fairy shrimps to detect and solve species complexes.

Although the monophyly of Streptocephalus seems to be well supported (
Weekers et al . 2002
;
Daniels et al . 2004
), mtDNA data do not support a clear intrageneric structure, which drove
Daniels et al . (2004)
to reject previous subdivisions within the genus based on morphological characters ( Daday 1910a ;
Brendonck et al . 1992
). However, Rogers (2013) retained
Brendonck et al . (1992)
subgeneric proposal that considers the genus to be subdivided into two subgenera: Streptocephalus s. str. and ParastreptocephalusBrendonck, Hamer & Thiéry, 1992 .

The intrageneric structure of Streptocephalus is however far from clear and many groups have been created as subgenera using different morphological characters ( Daday 1910a ;
Brendonck et al. 1992
;
Hamer et al. 1994a
, b;
Maeda-Martínez et al. 1995b
). However, molecular analyses reject those morphological divisions (
Daniels et al . 2004
). The characters that define subgenus Parastreptocephalus are the tetrahedral shape of the eggs, and a unique male antennal morphology (
Brendonck et al. 1992
). Three species of Parastreptocephalus are present in southern Africa, while one is present in Australia . Phylogenetic studies have verified a common origin of the African S. sudanicus and the Australian S. archeriSars, 1896 (
Daniels et al. 2004
; Timms 2015 ). Although all species included in Parastreptocephalus are likely to share a common ancestor by sharing the synapomorphy of having tetrahedral eggs, the entire Parastreptocephalus clade is deeply nested inside a clade of species that produce spherical eggs, corresponding to Streptocephalus s. str. (
).
Daniels et al . (2004)
rejected the use of this character as a taxonomical trait to identify subgenera. However, as
Maeda-Martínez et al. (1995a)
demonstrated, the genus can be split in cohesive morphological units, most of them in agreement with previous subdivisions. One of these well morphologically defined groups corresponds to Streptocephalopsis , a subgenus proposed by Daday (1910a) which includes S. zeltneri and S. wolof , and that according to our phylogenetic analyses is sister to all the Streptocephalus analysed. Under the current circumstances of lack of information, and considering the evidence that Parastreptocephalus is deeply nested within Streptocephalus s. str. , while Streptocephalopsis is sister to all other Streptocephalus we concur with
Daniels et al . (2004)
and recommend not to consider any subgeneric subdivision within Streptocephalus until more information is available.
